    <h2>When to Use Brave Search</h2>
    <p style="color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      Use Brave Search when you need broad search capabilities across multiple content types. Six specialized tools mean Claude picks the right search method automatically — web for general queries, news for current events, image and video for media, local for businesses. The 2,000 free queries per month is the most generous free tier in the search MCP category. Best for general-purpose search where variety of results matters more than LLM optimization.
    </p>

    <h2>When to Use Tavily</h2>
    <p style="color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      Use Tavily when Claude needs search results it can reason about immediately. Results come pre-processed — ads stripped, navigation removed, content extracted — so Claude spends tokens on analysis, not parsing. The extract, map, and crawl tools go beyond simple search into site analysis territory. Best for AI agent workflows, research tasks, and situations where result quality matters more than result variety.
    </p>

    <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
    <p style="color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      Brave Search gives Claude more ways to search. Tavily gives Claude better results to work with. For casual "look this up" queries, Brave's larger free tier and six tool types make it the easier default. For AI agent pipelines and deep research, Tavily's LLM-optimized output produces better downstream results. Many developers run both — they serve different search needs and don't conflict.
    </p>

